## Unit 3 Day 15-16: HTML and CSS â€“ Tables, Lists, Menus 

First, let's explore the eighth lesson in the curriculum. To begin, find your ECS Version 5 curriculum and open to page 117-118.

<a href="http://code.org/ecs#page=117" target="_blank">Access a Digital Copy of the Lesson >></a>


#### Key Concepts

1. Students will learn table, row and column tagging in an html page and how to add css styling to the html table

2. Students will use ordered and unordered list tagging in an html page and add css styling to html list elements

3. Students will use grid elements in css div placement and add a menu to an html page

#### Common Difficulties

Before presenting this lesson you will need to go the tutorials listed in the lesson ( [http://www.georgebenainous.com/web](http://www.georgebenainous.com/web) html/css---tables, styled lists, page layout, menus), and be prepared to demonstrate: tables in an html page and how to add css styling, ordered and unordered list and how to add css styling to list elements, in addition to , div positioning using css and how to create menus.  The tutorials will help you prepare you for a discussion with the students on predicting what changes may look like on a web page before they actually apply them (this may remind them of storyboarding or using the problem solving process - common things a computer scientist must do often).

You will also need to think of data that lends itself to be in a table on a website, in addition to examples of menus someone may want to add.

